BUILD ORDER — FOLLOW THIS EXACTLY
(each phase unblocks the next — do not skip ahead)

Phase 1 — Contract fix + deploy to live appchain
Phase 2 — Frontend scaffold + 4 core hooks (unblocks all screen work)
Phase 3 — Screens: Landing → Profile → Games → DEX → Marketplace → Gas Panel
Phase 4 — Native Initia features: Auto-signing → Usernames → Bridge
Phase 5 — Polish, security checks, error states
Phase 6 — PXL gas token migration (last infrastructure step — only after everything works)
Phase 7 — Submission package: README + submission.json + demo video

---

BEFORE YOU BUILD ANYTHING — UNDERSTAND THE PRODUCT

PixelVault is a cross-game player economy on Initia MiniEVM. Think of it like this:

You mint a Profile NFT. That NFT gets its own wallet (a "Token Bound Account" — TBA).
Every game item, game token, and badge you earn goes into that wallet — not your browser wallet.
That's the key idea. Your identity IS the NFT. Your inventory IS the TBA.

Here's every piece of the system and what it actually does:

PlayerProfile
  You mint one NFT per wallet. The contract auto-creates a TBA (wallet) for that NFT
  via ERC-6551. This TBA is where all your stuff lives.

TBA (Token Bound Account)
  Your game wallet. Owned by the NFT, controlled by your browser wallet (EOA).
  Items, tokens, badges — everything goes here. Your EOA never holds game assets directly.

PXL Token
  The base currency. Every game token trades against PXL on the DEX. Later in the
  build, PXL becomes the chain's gas token too.

GameRegistry
  A registry of all games on the platform. When a game is registered, the registry
  auto-deploys a game-specific ERC20 token and an ERC1155 item collection for it.

PixelVaultDEX
  A simple AMM (like a tiny Uniswap). Players swap PXL for game tokens and vice versa.
  The DEX also tracks trade volume, which feeds into game ratings.

GasPaymaster
  This is the clever part. Players can pay gas fees in any game token (say, DNGN)
  instead of PXL. The paymaster swaps it to PXL behind the scenes. Players never
  need to hold gas tokens.

AchievementBadge
  Soulbound (non-transferable) ERC1155 badges. Games mint these when players hit
  milestones. Badges build a reputation score.

Marketplace
  Players list and buy ERC1155 items. Buyers can pay in ANY game token — the
  marketplace auto-swaps to PXL internally via the DEX.

DungeonDrops (demo game 1)
  Pay 10 DNGN, roll for loot. 60% Common Sword, 30% Rare Shield, 10% Legendary
  Crown. Items land in your TBA.

HarvestField (demo game 2)
  Stake HRV tokens, wait 100 blocks, harvest your reward + a seasonal item.
  Also lands in your TBA.


HOW EVERY GAME ACTION ACTUALLY WORKS (read this twice)

Every single game action follows this exact path:

  Your browser wallet (EOA)
    → calls TBA.execute(gameContractAddress, 0, calldata, 0)
      → TBA forwards the call to the game contract (DungeonDrops, HarvestField, etc.)
        → game contract does its thing (mints items, badges, etc.)
          → items land in the TBA

So when someone clicks "Enter Dungeon" on the frontend, what actually happens is:
1. The frontend encodes the enterDungeon() function call into raw bytes (calldata)
2. It wraps that in tba.execute(DungeonDrops address, 0, calldata, 0)
3. The player's EOA signs and sends that execute() call
4. The TBA receives it, sees the player owns the NFT, and forwards the call to DungeonDrops
5. DungeonDrops does the loot roll and mints items to the caller (the TBA)

This is why the frontend always needs three things:
  - The player's TBA address → from PlayerProfile.getTBA(tokenId)
  - The encoded calldata → use viem's encodeFunctionData()
  - A call to tba.execute() → signed by the EOA

If you don't get this flow, nothing else will make sense. Re-read it.

===================================================================================
PHASE 1 — CONTRACT FIX + APPCHAIN DEPLOYMENT
One person does this. Everyone else waits for the deployed-addresses.json file.
===================================================================================

The contracts are written and tested. But there's one missing piece, and then
they need to be deployed to the live appchain. Once deployed, this phase produces
a deployed-addresses.json file. That file is what every frontend hook imports.
Without it, nobody can start on frontend.

--- Step 1A: Add ownerToTokenId to PlayerProfile.sol ---

Right now there's no way to look up "which tokenId does this wallet own?" from
the contract. The frontend needs this to load a player's profile. It's 3 lines.

Open contracts/PlayerProfile.sol.

Find the state variables (around line 43, near `mapping(address => bool) public hasMinted`).
Add this line right below it:

  mapping(address => uint256) public ownerToTokenId;

Then find the mint() function. After the line that says `_safeMint(msg.sender, tokenId)`,
add:

  ownerToTokenId[msg.sender] = tokenId;

That's it. Recompile and run all tests:

  npx hardhat test

Everything should still pass. If it doesn't, you broke something — diff your changes.

--- Step 1B: Set up .env for deployment ---

Create a .env file in the project root (same folder as hardhat.config.ts).
NEVER commit this to GitHub. Add it to .gitignore if it's not already there.

  MINIEVM_RPC_URL=http://localhost:8545
  PRIVATE_KEY=<your hex private key — see below>
  CHAIN_ID=<your chain ID — see below>

How to get your private key:
Your gas station mnemonic is stored in ~/.weave/config.json. To extract the
hex private key that Hardhat needs, run:

  initiad keys export gas-station --unsafe --unarmored-hex --keyring-backend test

Copy the hex output. Prefix it with 0x if it doesn't have one already.

How to get your chain ID:
Make sure your appchain is running, then:

  curl localhost:8545 -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"jsonrpc":"2.0","method":"eth_chainId","id":1}'

The result is a hex number. Convert it to decimal (e.g., 0x539 = 1337) and
put that in CHAIN_ID.


--- Step 1C: Start appchain and deploy ---

1. Start the rollup node (if it's not already running):

   weave rollup start -d

   Verify it's alive:
   curl localhost:8545 -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
     -d '{"jsonrpc":"2.0","method":"eth_blockNumber","id":1}'

   You should get back a hex block number. If you get "connection refused",
   the node isn't running yet — wait a minute and try again.

2. Start OPinit and Relayer (needed for bridge feature later):

   weave opinit start executor -d
   weave relayer start -d

3. Add your appchain network to hardhat.config.ts:

   Inside the `config` object, add a `networks` section:

   networks: {
     minievm: {
       url: process.env.MINIEVM_RPC_URL,
       accounts: [process.env.PRIVATE_KEY],
       chainId: Number(process.env.CHAIN_ID)
     }
   }

4. Deploy all contracts:

   npx hardhat run scripts/deploy.ts --network minievm

   Watch the console. Every contract should print its address. If any fail,
   read the error — usually it's "insufficient funds" (your gas station
   needs INIT) or "nonce too high" (restart the node).

5. Wire contracts together:

   npx hardhat run scripts/wire.ts --network minievm

   This sets up permissions — which contracts can mint items, which can
   issue badges, etc. If you skip this, games won't work.

6. Verify the deployment:

   Create a script called scripts/verify.ts. Have it call one read function
   on every contract and log the result. For example:
   - playerProfile.totalPlayers()
   - gameRegistry.getGameCount()
   - pxlToken.totalSupply()

   Run it:
   npx hardhat run scripts/verify.ts --network minievm

   If you see numbers (not errors), you're good.

7. Push deployed-addresses.json to GitHub:

   This is the file the deploy script writes. It has every contract address.
   Push it so teammates can pull and start building the frontend immediately.

   git add deployed-addresses.json
   git commit -m "deployed addresses for live appchain"
   git push

NOTE: We are NOT doing the PXL gas token migration (PXLTokenInitia.sol) here.
That's Phase 6 — the last thing before recording the demo. Using the standard
PXLToken is correct for now. Don't touch PXLTokenInitia until Phase 6.


===================================================================================
PHASE 2 — FRONTEND FOUNDATION
Scaffold the project + build 4 hooks. Everything else depends on these.
===================================================================================

--- Step 2A: Project scaffold ---

Inside the repo, create a frontend/ folder and scaffold:

  mkdir frontend && cd frontend
  npm create vite@latest . -- --template react-ts
  npm install @initia/interwovenkit-react wagmi viem @tanstack/react-query @initia/initia.js
  npm install vite-plugin-node-polyfills
  npm install tailwindcss @tailwindcss/vite

Set up vite.config.ts with node polyfills. Blockchain libraries use Node.js
APIs (Buffer, crypto, etc.) that don't exist in the browser. The polyfill
plugin fakes them. Look at the MiniBank EVM blueprint (Blueprints-Minibank EVM.txt
in this repo) — it has the exact vite config pattern. Copy it.

For main.tsx / App.tsx provider setup, also copy from the MiniBank blueprint.
You need three nested providers:
  QueryClientProvider (from @tanstack/react-query)
    → WagmiProvider
      → InterwovenKitProvider

Replace the chain ID and token denom with your appchain's values (from your
.env or deployed-addresses.json).


--- Step 2B: lib/addresses.ts ---

Create frontend/src/lib/addresses.ts. This is the ONE place all contract
addresses come from. Nothing else should hardcode addresses.

  import deployed from '../../../deployed-addresses.json';
  export const ADDRESSES = deployed;

(Adjust the relative path depending on your folder structure — it should
point to the deployed-addresses.json file from Phase 1.)


--- Step 2C: lib/abis/ folder ---

The frontend needs to know what functions each contract has. That information
lives in the ABI (Application Binary Interface) — a JSON array that describes
every function, event, and input.

1. After compiling (npx hardhat compile), look in artifacts/contracts/. Each
   contract has a .json file with an "abi" field inside it.

2. Create frontend/src/lib/abis/. For each contract, copy just the "abi"
   array into a new JSON file. Example: PlayerProfile.json contains
   { "abi": [...] }.

3. Create an index.ts that re-exports everything:

   export { abi as PlayerProfileABI } from './PlayerProfile.json';
   export { abi as DungeonDropsABI } from './DungeonDrops.json';
   export { abi as HarvestFieldABI } from './HarvestField.json';
   export { abi as MarketplaceABI } from './Marketplace.json';
   export { abi as PixelVaultDEXABI } from './PixelVaultDEX.json';
   export { abi as GameRegistryABI } from './GameRegistry.json';
   export { abi as AchievementBadgeABI } from './AchievementBadge.json';
   export { abi as GasPaymasterABI } from './GasPaymaster.json';
   export { abi as PXLTokenABI } from './PXLToken.json';
   export { abi as ERC6551AccountABI } from './ERC6551Account.json';
   export { abi as CommonRelicABI } from './CommonRelic.json';
   export { abi as GameAssetCollectionABI } from './GameAssetCollection.json';

This is how viem (the library we use for contract calls) knows what functions
exist on each contract.


--- Step 2D: The 4 Core Hooks ---

These are React hooks (functions that start with "use"). Every screen depends
on at least one of them. Build and test all four before touching any screen.

~~ Hook 1: useContracts.ts ~~

What it does:
  Returns a ready-to-use contract object for every deployed contract.
  Other hooks call this instead of manually setting up contract connections.

How it works:
  Uses viem's getContract() with the addresses from lib/addresses.ts and
  ABIs from lib/abis/. Takes the wagmi publicClient (for reads) and
  walletClient (for writes) as inputs.

What to tell the AI:
  "Build a React hook called useContracts. Use viem's getContract to create
  typed instances of PlayerProfile, GameRegistry, PixelVaultDEX, DungeonDrops,
  HarvestField, AchievementBadge, GasPaymaster, Marketplace, PXLToken,
  CommonRelic, and ERC6551Account. Import addresses from lib/addresses.ts
  and ABIs from lib/abis/index.ts. Accept publicClient and walletClient as
  parameters. Return an object with all contract instances."


~~ Hook 2: usePlayerProfile.ts ~~

What it does:
  THE most important hook. Checks if the connected wallet has a profile.
  If yes, returns their tokenId, TBA address, username, and reputation score.
  If no, returns {hasProfile: false} so the UI can show a "Create Profile" screen.

How it works:
  1. Gets the connected wallet address from InterwovenKit (useInterwovenKit())
  2. Calls playerProfile.hasMinted(address) — returns true/false
  3. If true, calls playerProfile.ownerToTokenId(address) → tokenId
  4. Calls playerProfile.getTBA(tokenId) → TBA wallet address
  5. Calls playerProfile.usernames(tokenId) → display name
  6. Calls achievementBadge.getReputation(tba) → reputation score
  7. Exposes a mint(username) function for creating new profiles

What to tell the AI:
  "Build a React hook called usePlayerProfile. Get the connected wallet
  address from useInterwovenKit(). Call playerProfile.read.hasMinted([address]).
  If false, return {hasProfile: false}. If true, call ownerToTokenId(address)
  to get tokenId, getTBA(tokenId) for TBA address, usernames(tokenId) for
  display name, and achievementBadge.getReputation(tba) for reputation.
  Return {hasProfile, tokenId, tba, username, reputation, mint}. The mint
  function should call requestTxBlock with a MsgCall to PlayerProfile.mint(username)
  using encodeFunctionData from viem. Import PlayerProfileABI from lib/abis
  and ADDRESSES from lib/addresses."


~~ Hook 3: useTBA.ts ~~

What it does:
  This is how the frontend executes game actions. EVERY game action
  (enterDungeon, stake, harvest, listItem, buyItem) goes through this hook.
  It wraps the action in tba.execute() so the TBA forwards it to the game
  contract.

Why it exists:
  Players don't call game contracts directly. They call their TBA, and the
  TBA calls the game contract on their behalf. This hook hides that complexity.
  When a screen wants to call enterDungeon(), it just does:
    tba.execute(DungeonDrops.address, 0n, encodedCalldata)
  ...and this hook handles the TBA wrapping and signing.

How it works:
  Gets the player's TBA address from usePlayerProfile(). Exposes an execute()
  function that encodes TBA.execute(target, value, calldata, 0) and sends it
  via requestTxBlock.

What to tell the AI:
  "Build a React hook called useTBA. Get the tba address from usePlayerProfile().
  Expose one function: execute(target: string, value: bigint, calldata: Hex).
  Internally, encode ERC6551Account.execute(target, value, calldata, 0) using
  encodeFunctionData with ERC6551AccountABI. Then call requestTxBlock from
  useInterwovenKit() with a message of typeUrl '/minievm.evm.v1.MsgCall',
  sender = initiaAddress, contractAddr = tba address, input = the encoded
  data. Return {execute, isPending}."


~~ Hook 4: useAutoSign.ts ~~

What it does:
  Makes auto-signing work. Without this, every "Enter Dungeon" click pops up
  a wallet confirmation dialog. With auto-signing, the player approves one
  session and then clicks freely — no popups.

How it works:
  Uses InterwovenKit's session key API to create a time-limited session
  (1 hour) scoped to the player's TBA address. Since all game actions go
  through the TBA, one session covers every game.

What to tell the AI:
  "Build a React hook called useAutoSign using @initia/interwovenkit-react.
  Use InterwovenKit's session key API to create a session scoped to the
  player's TBA address (from usePlayerProfile().tba). Expose: grantSession()
  which opens the approval flow, isSessionActive boolean, and revokeSession().
  Set session expiry to 1 hour. Look up the exact session key hook name in
  the interwovenkit-react package — it might be called useSessionKey or
  useSession or similar."


--- Step 2E: ProfileGate component ---

Most screens require the player to have a profile. Build a wrapper component
called ProfileGate that:
  - Shows a spinner while usePlayerProfile is loading
  - If hasProfile is false → redirects to /create-profile
  - If hasProfile is true → renders whatever is inside it (children)

Wrap every route except the landing page with this. That way nobody can reach
the DungeonDrops page without a profile.


--- Step 2F: Test before moving on ---

Don't start building screens until hooks work. Make a throwaway /debug page
that dumps the raw output of all 4 hooks on screen. Something like:

  tokenId: 3
  TBA: 0xabc...
  username: AliceGamer
  reputation: 150
  auto-sign active: false

If you can see those values after minting a profile, the foundation is solid.
Delete the debug page later.


===================================================================================
PHASE 3 — SCREENS
Build them in this order. The first three are needed for the demo video.
===================================================================================

Important: every screen below has an "AI PROMPT" section. That's a ready-to-paste
prompt for your AI assistant. Feed it as-is or tweak it if needed. The prompts
include specific contract functions and data flows so the AI doesn't hallucinate.


--- Screen 0: Wallet Connect (Landing Page) ---

The first thing users see. A "Connect Wallet" button. That's it.

What to show:
  PixelVault logo/title, a tagline ("The cross-game player economy on Initia"),
  and a Connect Wallet button. Nothing else.

How it works:
  - No contract calls here. Purely UI.
  - Uses useInterwovenKit() → openConnect() to trigger the wallet popup.
  - After connection, check usePlayerProfile().hasProfile:
      if true → go to /profile
      if false → go to /create-profile

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React landing page for PixelVault. Show a centered card with title
  'PixelVault', subtitle 'The cross-game player economy on Initia', and a
  'Connect Wallet' button that calls openConnect() from useInterwovenKit().
  After connecting (when initiaAddress is set), check hasProfile from
  usePlayerProfile — navigate to /profile if true, /create-profile if false.
  Tailwind CSS, dark theme, background color #1A1A2E."


--- Screen 1: Create Profile ---

One-time screen. The player picks a username and mints their Profile NFT.
After minting, the contract creates their TBA automatically.

What to show:
  - Username text input (3-20 characters, alphanumeric only)
  - "Create Profile" button
  - Brief explanation: "This creates your game wallet (TBA). All your items,
    tokens, and badges will live here."

How it works:
  - This is the ONLY screen where the player's EOA calls a contract directly.
    Every other screen uses the TBA via useTBA(). Here we call
    PlayerProfile.mint(username) straight from the EOA.
  - After success, usePlayerProfile re-fetches and returns the new TBA address.
  - Redirect to /profile.

What goes wrong:
  - "Already minted" error → player already has a profile. Redirect them.
  - "Username: 3-20 chars" → client-side validation prevents this, but show
    the contract error if it slips through.

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React CreateProfile component. Text input for username — validate
  3-20 chars, alphanumeric, client-side before submit. On submit, call
  requestTxBlock from useInterwovenKit() with a MsgCall to PlayerProfile.mint(username).
  Encode calldata with encodeFunctionData from viem using PlayerProfileABI.
  Contract address from ADDRESSES.PlayerProfile. Show loading spinner while
  pending. On success, display the new TBA address from usePlayerProfile().tba
  and a 'Go to Dashboard' button. On error, show the revert reason.
  Tailwind CSS, dark theme."


--- Screen 2: Profile Dashboard (HERO SCREEN) ---

This is the money screen. Judges will spend the most time here. It shows
everything about a player: tokens, items, badges, reputation, activity.

It has 5 sections. Each one reads from different contracts:

  1) Profile Card
     - Username: playerProfile.usernames(tokenId)
     - Reputation score: achievementBadge.getReputation(tba)
     - TBA address (show truncated, with copy button)

  2) Token Balances
     - PXL: pxlToken.balanceOf(tba)
     - DNGN: dungeonToken.balanceOf(tba)   (address from ADDRESSES.DungeonDropsToken)
     - HRV: harvestToken.balanceOf(tba)    (address from ADDRESSES.HarvestFieldToken)

  3) Inventory (Items)
     - DungeonDrops items: call balanceOf(tba, 1), balanceOf(tba, 2), balanceOf(tba, 3)
       on the DungeonDrops GameAssetCollection (ADDRESSES.DungeonDropsAssets)
       Item names: 1 = Common Sword, 2 = Rare Shield, 3 = Legendary Crown
     - HarvestField items: balanceOf(tba, 1) on ADDRESSES.HarvestFieldAssets
       Item name: 1 = Seasonal Harvest

  4) Badges
     - achievementBadge.balanceOf(tba, 1) → "First Clear" badge
     - achievementBadge.balanceOf(tba, 2) → "First Harvest" badge
     - Show as badge cards. If balance is 0, show greyed out or don't show.

  5) Activity Feed
     - Get recent DungeonEntered and Harvested events using publicClient.getLogs
       filtered to the player's TBA address. Show the last 5 with timestamps.

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React ProfileDashboard component. Use usePlayerProfile() for tokenId,
  tba, username, reputation. For token balances, use publicClient.readContract
  to call balanceOf(tba) on PXLToken (ADDRESSES.PXLToken), DungeonDrops token
  (ADDRESSES.DungeonDropsToken), and HarvestField token (ADDRESSES.HarvestFieldToken)
  — all using the standard ERC20 ABI. For items, call balanceOf(tba, itemId)
  on the ERC1155 asset collections at ADDRESSES.DungeonDropsAssets (items 1,2,3)
  and ADDRESSES.HarvestFieldAssets (item 1) — use the ERC1155 ABI.
  For badges, call achievementBadge.balanceOf(tba, 1) and (tba, 2).
  For activity, use publicClient.getLogs with DungeonDrops and HarvestField
  contract addresses. Render 5 sections: profile card, token balances (3-column
  grid), inventory (item cards with names), badges (badge cards), activity feed
  (last 5 events). Tailwind CSS, dark theme. Add loading skeletons while data
  is fetching."


--- Screen 3: DungeonDrops ---

The primary game. Click "Enter Dungeon", pay 10 DNGN, get random loot.
This is where auto-signing shines — rapid clicks with no wallet popups.

Data to show:
  - Entry fee: 10 DNGN (hardcoded — it's a constant in the contract)
  - Player's DNGN balance (ERC20 balanceOf at TBA address)
  - Total global runs: DungeonDrops.totalRuns()
  - Player's run count: DungeonDrops.playerNonce(tba)
  - Drop rates: 60% Common Sword, 30% Rare Shield, 10% Legendary Crown

How the transaction works:
  1. Encode enterDungeon() calldata using encodeFunctionData + DungeonDropsABI
  2. Call useTBA().execute(ADDRESSES.DungeonDrops, 0n, calldata)
  3. Wait for tx to confirm
  4. Read the DungeonEntered event from the receipt → get the itemId
  5. Map itemId to name and show a loot reveal animation

Auto-signing:
  If useAutoSign().isSessionActive is true, show a green badge "Auto-sign ON".
  Entering the dungeon won't pop up the wallet dialog — it just goes.
  If it's off, show a "Start auto-sign" button.

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React DungeonDrops component. Use useTBA().execute to call
  enterDungeon() on the DungeonDrops contract (ADDRESSES.DungeonDrops).
  Encode calldata with encodeFunctionData using DungeonDropsABI. Show:
  DNGN balance at TBA (ERC20 balanceOf), 10 DNGN entry fee, total runs from
  DungeonDrops.totalRuns(), player run count from DungeonDrops.playerNonce(tba).
  After tx success, parse the DungeonEntered event from the receipt to get
  itemId. Map: 1=Common Sword, 2=Rare Shield, 3=Legendary Crown. Show an
  animated loot reveal (CSS transition: a chest opens to show the item).
  Include a static drop rates table (60/30/10). Show auto-sign status from
  useAutoSign() — green badge if active, toggle button if not.
  Tailwind CSS, dark theme."


--- Screen 4: HarvestField ---

A staking game. Three different UI states depending on what the player is doing.

  State 1 — Not staking:
    Show HRV balance, an amount input, and a "Stake" button.

  State 2 — Staking (waiting):
    Show staked amount, which block they staked at, the current block, and a
    progress bar (blocksElapsed / 100). Poll publicClient.getBlockNumber()
    every 5 seconds to update the progress live. Show estimated reward.
    "Harvest" button is disabled. "Unstake" button is available.

  State 3 — Ready to harvest (100+ blocks passed):
    "Harvest" button turns green and is enabled. Show final reward amount.

Contract reads:
  HarvestField.stakes(tba) → returns {amount, stakedAtBlock}
  publicClient.getBlockNumber() → current block
  Reward formula: (amount × 1e16 × blocksElapsed) / 1e18

How transactions work (all through useTBA):
  Stake:   tba.execute(HarvestField, 0n, encode('stake', [amount]))
  Harvest: tba.execute(HarvestField, 0n, encode('harvest'))
  Unstake: tba.execute(HarvestField, 0n, encode('unstake'))

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React HarvestField component with 3 UI states. Read
  HarvestField.stakes(tba) — if amount is 0, show stake form. If amount > 0
  and currentBlock < stakedAtBlock + 100, show waiting state with a progress
  bar (blocksElapsed / 100 blocks) and reward estimate. If currentBlock >=
  stakedAtBlock + 100, enable Harvest button (green). Poll getBlockNumber()
  every 5 seconds for live progress. All actions use useTBA().execute()
  with encoded calldata. Import HarvestFieldABI and ADDRESSES.
  Tailwind CSS, dark theme."


--- Screen 5: PixelVault DEX ---

Token exchange page. Players swap PXL for game tokens and back.

Parts:
  1) Swap form: token selector (PXL, DNGN, HRV), amount input, estimated
     output. Use dex.getPrice(gameId) for the rate.

  2) Pool info: Show pool reserves from dex.pools(gameId) — how much PXL
     and how much game token are in each pool.

  3) Liquidity tab: Add/remove liquidity. addLiquidity(gameId, pxlAmount,
     maxGameAmount) and removeLiquidity(gameId, shareAmount).

  4) Bridge button: One line of code that opens the Initia bridge modal:
     openBridge({ srcChainId: 'initiation-2', srcDenom: 'uinit' })
     InterwovenKit provides the entire bridge UI. You don't build it.

Important — gameId values:
  Game IDs are keccak256 hashes, not strings. Compute them in JS:
    import { keccak256, toUtf8Bytes } from 'ethers';
    const DUNGEON_GAME_ID = keccak256(toUtf8Bytes('DungeonDrops'));
    const HARVEST_GAME_ID = keccak256(toUtf8Bytes('HarvestField'));

How swaps work (through useTBA):
  Swap PXL → game token:
    1. Approve PXL for the DEX: tba.execute(pxlToken, 0, encode('approve', [dex, amount]))
    2. Call swap:               tba.execute(dex, 0, encode('swapPXLForGame', [gameId, amount, minOut]))

  Swap game token → PXL:
    1. Approve game token for DEX
    2. Call swapGameForPXL

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React DEX component. Token selector: PXL, DNGN (gameId =
  keccak256('DungeonDrops')), HRV (gameId = keccak256('HarvestField')).
  Compute gameIds with ethers.id(). Show swap rate from dex.read.getPrice(gameId).
  For swapPXLForGame: use useTBA to first encode an approve call on PXL token,
  then encode the swap call. Show pool reserves from dex.read.pools(gameId).
  Add a tab for add/remove liquidity. Add a 'Bridge INIT' button that calls
  openBridge({srcChainId: 'initiation-2', srcDenom: 'uinit'}) from
  useInterwovenKit(). Tailwind CSS, dark theme."


--- Screen 6: Marketplace ---

Item trading page. Players list ERC1155 items for sale and buy others' items.
Buyers can pay in any game token — the Marketplace auto-swaps to PXL via DEX.

Browsing:
  - Read Marketplace.nextListingId() to get total count
  - Loop and call Marketplace.listings(id) for each
  - Show only listings where active == true
  - For each: item name, game origin, seller username, quantity, price in PXL

Listing an item:
  1. Player picks an item from their inventory
  2. Sets a price in PXL
  3. Two calls via useTBA:
     a. setApprovalForAll(Marketplace address, true) on the item collection
     b. Marketplace.listItem(collection, itemId, amount, priceInPXL, gameId)

Buying with PXL:
  1. Approve PXL → Marketplace for the total price
  2. Marketplace.buyItem(listingId, amount, pxlTokenAddress, total)
  Both via useTBA.

Buying with a game token (the cool part):
  Call Marketplace.buyItem(listingId, amount, gameTokenAddress, maxPayment).
  Set maxPayment using dex.getAmountIn(). The contract handles the swap internally.

Cancelling:
  Marketplace.cancelListing(listingId) — only show this button if the
  listing's seller address matches the player's TBA.

Fee info:
  2.5% fee taken from the seller's proceeds. Buyer pays the listed price.
  Seller receives price × 0.975.

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a React Marketplace component. Fetch all listings: call
  marketplace.read.nextListingId() for count, then read each listing. Show
  active ones in a grid. For seller names, look up ownerToTokenId on
  PlayerProfile to get their tokenId, then usernames(tokenId).
  'Buy with PXL' button: encode PXL approve + buyItem, both via useTBA.
  'List Item' modal: show player's ERC1155 balances at TBA address, let
  them pick quantity and PXL price, then call setApprovalForAll + listItem
  via useTBA. Show 2.5% fee breakdown. Tailwind CSS, dark theme."


