===================================================================================
PHASE 4 — NATIVE INITIA FEATURES
These make PixelVault an Initia-native product, not just "another EVM app."
===================================================================================

--- 4A: Auto-signing (REQUIRED for demo — Priority 1) ---

This is the feature that makes DungeonDrops feel like a real game instead of
a "click-and-confirm-in-wallet" slog. The player approves one session, then
every Enter Dungeon click goes through instantly.

How it works:
  InterwovenKit has a session key API. You create a session scoped to a
  specific contract address. Since ALL game actions go through the player's
  TBA (not directly to DungeonDrops), you scope the session to the TBA address.
  One session = auto-sign for every game.

Where to add it in the UI:
  1. A "Start Auto-sign" button in the app header or on the Profile Dashboard
  2. A green "Auto-sign active" indicator on the DungeonDrops screen

Session settings:
  - Scope: player's TBA address (NOT the game contract address)
  - Expiry: 1 hour
  - After expiry: falls back to normal wallet popups

The useAutoSign hook from Phase 2 handles this. Just make sure it's wired
into the DungeonDrops screen and the header.


--- 4B: Initia Usernames (Priority 2 — nice-to-have) ---

Wherever you show an address (marketplace seller, activity feed, leaderboard),
try to resolve it to a human-readable .init username instead.

This is display-layer only — no contract changes needed.

  - InterwovenKit provides a username resolution API.
  - Build a utility function: resolveUsername(address) → returns .init name
    or falls back to truncated address (0x1234...abcd)
  - Cache results so you don't re-fetch the same address repeatedly

AI PROMPT:
  "Build a useUsernameResolver hook using @initia/interwovenkit-react. It
  accepts an array of addresses and returns a map of address → .init username
  (or truncated address fallback). Cache results in a React ref. Use
  InterwovenKit's built-in username resolution API."


--- 4C: Bridge (Priority 3 — minimal effort) ---

InterwovenKit gives you the entire bridge UI. All you do is add one button:

  openBridge({ srcChainId: 'initiation-2', srcDenom: 'uinit' })

Put it on the DEX page or Profile Dashboard. Done.

Prerequisites: OPinit executor and IBC relayer must be running from Phase 1.

Note: during local testing, the bridge modal might say your chain isn't
registered. That's expected for local appchains. You can still show the
button and mention in the demo that it works on deployed chains.


